<GUIClass name="CnEcSplitContainer" id="1cc12798-4b59-4aa3-8128-3ccf8326c399">
    <superclass name="BaseControl"/>
    <transient/>
    <sharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassSharedTransientAllowed/>
    <subclassTransientAllowed/>
    <transientAllowed/>
    <text>___________________________________________________________________________

              P R O P R I E T A R Y   N O T I C E

This software, in whole and in every part, is proprietary to Jade Software
Corporation Limited at Christchurch, New Zealand and is not to be
reproduced, used or disclosed except upon prior written permission of Jade
Software Corporation Limited.

  COPYRIGHT © JADE SOFTWARE CORPORATION LIMITED 2004 - ALL RIGHTS RESERVED
____________________________________________________________________________

Using this control, a developer can easily add a number of "resizable" controls to a form,
and have "splitter" bars between then available at runtime to allow the users to manually
resize the child controls as required.

As an example, a listbox on one side and a "thumbnail" table displaying details of the currently
selected listbox entry on the other can both be independently resized as necessary by the user.

After painting the control on the form, you can paint any two "child" controls on top of it,
and optionally specify (using the leftToRightRatio property) the initial percentage which the left 
hand or top control will occupy at form load time.  If no ratio is specified, then the initial ratio will
maintain the proportions of the widths/heights of the painted controls.

You must paint no more than two controls onto the container, otherwise an exception will be raised at
form load time.  If you require more than one split, then simply make one of the two child controls 
another CnEcSplitContainer, and have it containing the second and third resizable children.

At runtime, the control resizes the two children controls to fill the boundaries of the control,
adding a splitter bar between them which can be dragged by the mouse to the left or right, or from 
top to botton when the split is a horizontal one.

If either of the two child controls is invisible, then the splitter bar will not be created, and 
the visible control will be resized to fill the container.


Methods
-------

1. setLeftToRightRatio(integer);

	Call this method to set the value indicating the percent of the Split Container that is to
	be occupied by the left-hand or top child control.  The remainder of the control will be occupied 
	by the other control.

2. setupChildControls;

	Call this method if you have made runtime changes to the child controls that will affect the 
	appearance of the Split Container.  eg. if you have made one of the child controls invisible, or
	added or deleted one of the child controls.  This method will rebuild the contents of the control,
	and add/remove a splitter bar as necessary.

3. CnEcResizeContents;

	Call this method if you have made runtime changes to the dimensions of the Split Container, and
	it will resize the contained controls to retain the proportions of the child controls before the 
	resize occurred.  This method should be called by a form after a resize.


Design-Time Properties
----------------------

1. leftToRightRatio (Percent as integer)

	Value indicating the percent of the Split Container that is to be occupied by the left-hand or top
	child control.  The remainder of the control will be occupied by the other control.
	If left as the default (zero) then the ratios will be set at the relative proportions of the 
	widths/heights of the painted child controls.
	(refer to splitType below)

2. isSplitHorizontal (boolean)

	Indicates whether the split between the child controls is vertical (side by side) or horizontal
	(one above the other).  Default is false, or vertical split.
	
3. splitType (Integer - Class Constants SplitType_Ratio (0), SplitType_LockLeft (1), SplitType_LockRight (2)

	Determines what method is used on a resize of the container to move the splitter bar.
	Ratio		: The size of the left and right panes are adjusted to maintain the same ratio.
	LockLeft	: The size of the left pane is fixed and the size of the right pane is adjusted.
	LockRight	: The size of the right pane is fixed and the size of the left pane is adjusted.
	
	For LockLeft and LockRight there is a minimum size which the variable pane won't get adjusted less than.  If
	this size is reached the fixed size pane will be resized.  If the user subsequently resizes the control
	so that the fixed pane can be shown at its set size it will be.

Run-Time Properties
-------------------

1. leftToRightRatio (Percent as integer)

	Read-only value indicating the percent of the Split Container that is to be occupied by the 	
	left-hand child control.  The remainder of the control will be occupied by the other control.
	Not used to resize if the splitType &lt;&gt; SplitType_Ratio.


Events
------

1. splitterMove(pSplitContainer : CnEcSplitContainer input);

	This event is called by the control after a user mouse action has changed the position of
	the splitter bar.  This allows the form to trap the action, and perform some other user 
	logic.</text>
    <DbClassMap file="_usergui"/>
